Tripwire replaces president after one year


Comment


Updated on August 30, 2016 at  9:52 AM
Posted on August 23, 2016 at  7:05 AM





    
        
            By Mike Rogoway
mrogoway@oregonian.com
 The Oregonian/OregonLive





Two Tripwire executives are leaving the Portland company, including President Gus Malezis, who is exiting after just 13 months in the top job. His last day was Friday and he's been replaced by a veteran executive from Tripwire's parent company, Belden.
Tripwire sold for $710 million in December 2014 to Belden, a publicly traded Midwestern company that makes communications networking hardware. The Portland company's longtime chief executive, Jim Johnson, retired last summer.
The changes appear to indicate that Tripwire is being more tightly integrated into Belden as the Portland company works to expand beyond its traditional market protecting commercial activity online and adds safeguards for industrial equipment, too.
Malezis joined Tripwire in 2013, when it acquired a San Francisco network security company called nCircle. He became Tripwire's vice president of sales immediately following that deal, and Belden promoted him to president after Johnson retired. Malezis lives in Canada and had been running the Portland business from there.
"Gus, I think, wanted to be a CEO on his own. Being a president as a part of another company is just different," said Dwayne Melancon, Tripwire's chief technology officer.
Tripwire's new president is Dhrupad Trivedi, who has been a Belden executive since 2011 - for the past three years as president of industrial technology and cybersecurity. Trivedi was the Belden executive who led the Tripwire acquisition, and Melancon said having him in charge of the Portland company will give the business added heft within Belden.
Trivedi lives in the Bay Area and won't be moving to Portland, Melancon said, but will be a regular visitor. And he said plans call for keeping Tripwire's headquarters in Oregon.
Another top Tripwire executive, product management vice president Rod Murchison, is also leaving the company. Melancon said he believes Murchison is going to pursue "another cybersecurity opportunity." Murchison also lives in California.
Tripwire recorded $167.1 million in sales last year, according to Belden's financial filings, and $44.6 million in earnings before interest, taxes and some accounting costs. Sales in the first six months of 2016 totaled $80.8 million, up 5.3 percent from a year earlier.
Tripwire is among Portland's largest high-tech employers. It had 450 workers at the time of its sale, 250 of them at its headquarters downtown, and Melancon said numbers are roughly the same today.
-- Mike Rogoway
mrogoway@oregonian.com 503-294-7699 @rogoway



